It's OK to clap.

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:31.170
Not so OK to boo.

00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:32.030
OK?

00:01:32.030 --> 00:01:34.690
Hopefully that won't happen.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:39.380
I was born in 1960 in
Jacksonville, Florida.

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:41.480
My father was in the
Coast Guard.

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:43.450
And we moved around quite
a bit, because

00:01:43.450 --> 00:01:44.410
he was in the military.

00:01:44.410 --> 00:01:47.250
About every three years we
found ourselves in a new

00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:49.730
location, in a new
exciting place.

00:01:49.730 --> 00:01:52.350
And it's sort of a negative
and a positive, right?

00:01:52.350 --> 00:01:55.290
When you move around a lot, you
have the opportunity to

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:57.260
make new friends,
meet new people.

00:01:57.260 --> 00:01:59.580
It gives you this sense of
exploration that you don't get

00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:01.120
normally anywhere else.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:02.940
But by the same token, you don't
really have a whole lot

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:04.190
of lifelong friends.

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:10.699
My dad was an avid
outdoors guy.

00:02:10.699 --> 00:02:12.220
He grew up in Colorado.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:13.970
They used to take pack
mules out into

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:14.890
the middle of nowhere.

00:02:14.890 --> 00:02:17.950
They'd spend two or three weeks
as a family on vacation.

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:20.390
I know that sounds completely
foreign to us today that

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:23.400
somebody would do anything with
a pack mule, but that's

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:24.370
what they used to do.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:26.980
And so he instilled in
me this sense of

00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:29.240
exploration, which is fun.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:30.790
Honestly, it's fun.

00:02:30.790 --> 00:02:34.440
Sweat is a good thing.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.860
I got my first camera when
I was 12 years old.

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:40.720
And it was an old
Olympus OM-1.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:42.730
If you're wondering why I'm
only walking from here to

00:02:42.730 --> 00:02:44.770
here, it's because that's
the total width that

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:46.330
this camera can see.

00:02:46.330 --> 00:02:48.550
I would normally walk way over
there just to watch all your

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:53.270
head's turn, like at a tennis
match or something.

00:02:53.270 --> 00:02:59.110
But my dad's best friend,
Uncle Bill, he loved

00:02:59.110 --> 00:03:02.260
photography, absolutely
loved it.

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:07.960
And Uncle Bill saw my passion
for following him around and

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:09.830
seeing what he was doing.

00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:14.060
And he gave me his
old Olympus OM-1.

00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:16.020
I started doing black and white

00:03:16.020 --> 00:03:18.420
photography with Uncle Bill.

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:22.730
And my very first darkroom
was the bathroom.

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:24.750
I'm not joking, the bathroom.

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:28.110
I'd mix my chemicals
in the sink.

00:03:28.110 --> 00:03:30.990
I would have a little teeny tray
that I would do the one

00:03:30.990 --> 00:03:32.930
thing and then the
other thing.

00:03:32.930 --> 00:03:34.380
And I would hang it up.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:38.110
I would literally turn
on the light switch

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:41.030
to expose the material.

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:45.320
That was my first darkroom,
the bathroom, literally.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:47.750
And I shot black
and white film.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:49.890
Oh man, well, I still
do, right?

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:55.380
But about eight or nine years,
when I was 20, 21, somewhere

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:59.570
in there, I discovered that
black and white photography

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:01.690
became easy.

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:02.120
I don't know.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:06.170
Is that heresy to say that in
the heart of Ansel Adams land?

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.090
I don't know.

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:09.790
But color--

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:10.860
OK, think about--

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:11.600
well, I should ask.

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:12.680
Can I ask a couple
more questions?

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:15.280
Any photographers in the room?

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:16.790
Oh, quite a few.

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:19.269
Any of you actually
know who I am?

00:04:19.269 --> 00:04:20.720
Oh, a couple.

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:22.480
Sweet.

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:23.850
Hey, that Google stuff's
working.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:28.430
How many people shooting film?

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:31.810
All right.

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:33.060
How many shooting digital?

00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:37.703
Film is not dead.

00:04:37.703 --> 00:04:40.360
I'm just saying that.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:45.250
How many shooting digital,
thinking of going to film?

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:46.950
One guy.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:47.870
Really?

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:52.250
Look, I'm not counting an iPhone
as a digital camera.

00:04:52.250 --> 00:04:53.710
Are you guys?

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:55.000
I hope not.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:56.740
I hope that's not what you're
counting, because

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:57.990
that doesn't count.

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:05.570
Not realizing I had any talent
for photography whatsoever, I

00:05:05.570 --> 00:05:09.590
took the traditional route
and went to college.

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:11.650
I was always good in math.

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:17.070
Do I have any math majors
in the room?

00:05:17.070 --> 00:05:17.560
Sweet.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:19.990
My kind of people.

00:05:19.990 --> 00:05:22.250
I left my pocket protector
at home today.

00:05:26.030 --> 00:05:32.200
When I was going to school, I
met my wife at a dance during

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.470
the summer, a church dance.

00:05:34.470 --> 00:05:36.980
Went back to school.

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:38.650
Missed her a lot.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:45.320
Left my last semester of my
senior year to go back and ask

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.060
my wife to marry me.

00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:49.820
She was stupid enough
to say yes.

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:52.910
I was lucky enough
that she did.

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:56.750
When I came back to school, I
got called in after a couple

00:05:56.750 --> 00:05:58.560
weeks into the dean's office.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:05:59.710
Anyone ever get called into the

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:02.795
dean's office for anything?

00:06:02.795 --> 00:06:03.670
Yeah, I didn't think.

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:04.976
None of you.

00:06:04.976 --> 00:06:06.580
You're smarter than I am.

00:06:06.580 --> 00:06:10.380
And they sat me down and they
said, you know, something

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:12.190
about you is different.

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:15.800
We're not sure what, but you
used to be a C student.

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.730
You're getting straight A's.

00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:18.855
What's the deal?

00:06:18.855 --> 00:06:20.276
I don't know.

00:06:20.276 --> 00:06:22.566
I don't have a clue.

00:06:22.566 --> 00:06:25.950
A couple more weeks go by, maybe
almost a whole month.

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:31.060
I get called back in to the
dean's office, and he says,

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:33.820
something's different,
because your

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.660
professors, they love you.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:38.770
And quite frankly, they didn't
really used to like

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:41.600
you all that much.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.990
And I get called in another
three weeks, and he says,

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:47.370
would you stay on for
a master's degree?

00:06:47.370 --> 00:06:49.380
You've got to take this
applications test.

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:52.020
You've got to take a
theory test just

00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:53.440
to get in the program.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:55.000
But we'd like you to get in.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:55.860
And I'm like, oh no.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:56.700
I'm pff--

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:57.750
are you kidding?

00:06:57.750 --> 00:07:00.290
I'm so far in debt.

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:02.470
Anyone still in debt
for the college?

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.000
Yeah, me too.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.270
The cheapest money
you'll ever get.

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:09.740
Take forever to pay that off.

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:12.010
Finally he says, look,
just take the exams.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:13.020
So I took the exams.

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:17.020
I got like a 98 on the theory
and a 99 on the application.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:20.420
And I was feeling pretty good.

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:24.260
I'm in the statistics
department, minoring in

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:26.020
mathematics.

00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:29.970
I was so smart, I could
float across campus.

00:07:29.970 --> 00:07:31.430
That's how smart I was.

00:07:31.430 --> 00:07:34.440
Or at least that's
how smart I felt.

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:39.680
So they call me back in and they
say, have you ever heard

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:43.640
of the BYU outstanding
achievement scholarship?

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:46.520
Like I'd ever heard of any kind
of scholarship before.

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:48.460
Not-- no way.

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:52.310
They said, well, we applied
for it in your name.

00:07:52.310 --> 00:07:54.030
Can you do that?

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:55.360
Are you--

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:56.880
what do we call that today?

00:07:56.880 --> 00:07:58.130
That's like identity
theft, isn't it?

00:08:01.034 --> 00:08:03.300
They said, well, you got it.

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:07.090
You just got the Brigham Young
University Outstanding

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:08.640
Achievement Scholarship.

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:12.054
I said, that's wonderful,
but what is it?

00:08:12.054 --> 00:08:13.330
Oh, simple.

00:08:13.330 --> 00:08:15.310
It pays for everything.

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:16.320
Everything?

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:17.230
Everything.

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:19.010
And we'll even give you
a job at $12 an hour.

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:21.750
Now realize, way back then, $12
an hour in the research

00:08:21.750 --> 00:08:23.870
center was a lot of money.

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:27.710
So after I got through
school, I went in--

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:30.630
I did graduate, just so you
know, a master's degree in

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:33.380
statistics with a minor
in mathematics.

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:36.320
So from one geek to the rest
of my fellow geeks in the

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:40.539
room, you don't have to remain
the way you are.

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:46.950
There is life outside
of geekdom.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:51.330
Because I'm not--

00:08:54.970 --> 00:08:56.010
well, how do I put it?

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:57.660
Because I can speak
corporate--

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.290
and you all know what
I mean by that--

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:00.690
actually, no.

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:03.230
You guys have a pretty cool
atmosphere here, don't you?

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:06.440
It's not too back-biting,
I hope.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:09.100
But because I could speak
corporate, and because I could

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:13.070
speak geek, I went up the
ladder pretty quick.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:16.960
And within seven years I was
director of database and

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:20.390
research for an international
direct mail marketing company

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:21.015
in New Jersey.

00:09:21.015 --> 00:09:22.680
Now, I'm from Oregon.

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:25.740
New Jersey is about as far away
from where I wanted to be

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:29.250
as I could possibly get.

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:32.610
Any managers in the room,
people who manage?

00:09:32.610 --> 00:09:33.330
A few.

00:09:33.330 --> 00:09:35.520
Well, the rest of you
are lucky, trust me.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:38.140
Because managing is not easy.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:44.680
It's kind of like wrangling
cats, managing kindergartners.

00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:45.640
All right?

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:48.190
You do realize that we
haven't changed.

00:09:48.190 --> 00:09:50.770
When you were in the sandbox at
four or five years old, and

00:09:50.770 --> 00:09:53.070
you were a yanking that toy
away from that other kid

00:09:53.070 --> 00:09:57.080
because it's mine, you
haven't changed.

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:00.060
You've gotten sneakier, but
we haven't changed.

00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:03.580
Basically, we're
still the same.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:07.190
Anyone know any Germans, I mean
born and bred, honest to

00:10:07.190 --> 00:10:10.160
goodness Germans?

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:15.590
These people have no sense
of social space at all.

00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:16.380
One day--

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:17.630
OK, write this down.

00:10:17.630 --> 00:10:19.430
You're going to need
this later in life.

00:10:22.390 --> 00:10:23.260
An hour--

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:24.680
I can't do this in an hour.

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:27.680
It's crazy.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:30.330
I'll speed up a little bit.

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:31.810
Write this down.

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.570
If you want to run a successful
business, here's

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:34.820
how you do it.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:36.660
You're going to have problems,
so you have to

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:39.590
identify the problem.

00:10:39.590 --> 00:10:42.250
Then you have to fix
the problem.

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:44.970
Then you have to not do
the problem again.

00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:45.590
That's it.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:47.500
That's how every successful
company on the face of the

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:49.870
plant operates, including
mine.

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:50.800
Identify the problem.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:51.720
Fix the problem.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:53.480
Don't do the problem again.

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:55.500
Every day as a manager,
I would have people

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:57.030
coming into my office.

00:10:57.030 --> 00:11:00.620
We have a problem,
and Susie did it.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:02.480
What are you going
to do to Susie?

00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:03.350
Oh, come on.

00:11:03.350 --> 00:11:05.000
Really?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.460
So one morning Jens--

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.610
born and bred, Munich--

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:12.160
comes in.

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:14.760
And Jens is like this
close to my face.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:15.630
He's so close.

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:19.270
And he's screaming about
something Susie has done, so

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:21.430
violently that the little
spit balls are

00:11:21.430 --> 00:11:22.680
hitting me in the face.

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:28.120
I snapped.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:29.330
I did.

00:11:29.330 --> 00:11:32.610
Jens, can you hold that
thought for a minute.

00:11:32.610 --> 00:11:34.680
I'll be right back.

00:11:34.680 --> 00:11:37.930
I marched down to the senior
VP of marketing, who I

00:11:37.930 --> 00:11:38.780
reported to.

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:40.720
She reported to the owners.

00:11:40.720 --> 00:11:42.450
Now realize that this time
I was in charge of

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:44.280
$164 million in sales.

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:48.900
I know that means nothing to
you guys being from Google.

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:52.310
That's like your budget,
isn't it, $164 million?

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:58.980
I had 30 people reporting to me
in 13 different countries,

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:01.150
and I snapped.

00:12:01.150 --> 00:12:04.850
I went down to her and I said,
I'm going to be leaving.

00:12:04.850 --> 00:12:05.900
She goes, what happened?

00:12:05.900 --> 00:12:09.880
I told her the spit balls.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.045
She said, no, you can't leave.

00:12:12.045 --> 00:12:14.575
I'm like, it's still America.

00:12:14.575 --> 00:12:16.195
I'm pretty sure I can.

00:12:16.195 --> 00:12:18.916
She goes, how much more
money do you want?

00:12:18.916 --> 00:12:20.365
What?

00:12:20.365 --> 00:12:24.740
Is that all I had to do to get
a raise, threaten to leave?

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:29.280
Holy crap, I wish I'd learned
that lesson sooner.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:32.290
I said no, no, no, no.

00:12:32.290 --> 00:12:33.830
I can't do this.

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:35.520
Well, when are you going
to leave, she asks.

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:45.140
About five minutes,
because I'm done.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:47.820
I helped them find
a replacement.

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:49.920
On the drive home--

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:51.340
oh, I should back
up a little bit.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:55.790
When you manage people, you're
sort of expected to do social

00:12:55.790 --> 00:12:57.310
events of some kind, right?

00:12:57.310 --> 00:12:58.655
We love to barbecue.

00:12:58.655 --> 00:13:01.620
If you ever come up to Oregon,
you want a good barbecue, just

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:04.500
call ahead so we can vacuum and
get the barbecue ready.

00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:09.170
People would come over
to the barbecue.

00:13:09.170 --> 00:13:13.240
They'd see something hanging on
a wall, and they'd be like,

00:13:13.240 --> 00:13:16.510
oh, that's amazing.

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:18.890
Where did you buy that?

00:13:18.890 --> 00:13:19.830
Buy it?

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:20.490
Are you kidding me?

00:13:20.490 --> 00:13:21.780
I'm Scottish.

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:23.820
I made that.

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:24.990
That's what us Scottish
people do.

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:26.360
We don't really buy stuff.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:29.680
We just make it, because
we're that cheap.

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:31.870
I'm sorry, frugal.

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:33.160
More of a Scottish
word, isn't it?

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:34.800
Frugal.

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:36.050
Get in my belly.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:41.660
So on the drive home I'm
thinking to myself, what am I

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:43.310
going to tell my wife.

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:46.140
We got three kids.

00:13:46.140 --> 00:13:48.610
They were paying me
$120,000 a year.

00:13:48.610 --> 00:13:51.712
This is back in '95, OK?

00:13:51.712 --> 00:13:53.540
That's a lot of money
back in '95.

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:55.720
And since I was in charge of
all the budgets and the

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:59.990
performance and the bonus
structure, guess

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:01.070
what else we made?

00:14:01.070 --> 00:14:03.310
Bonus every time.

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:05.580
So that was like another
$30,000.

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:08.180
I'm at $150,000 a year.

00:14:08.180 --> 00:14:09.500
We're living in the big house.

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:11.225
We got the sports
car, everything.

00:14:13.950 --> 00:14:14.690
Pull in the driveway.

00:14:14.690 --> 00:14:15.240
I get out.

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:16.540
I walk up the--

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:19.180
in the front door.

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:21.000
My wife hears the door
shut and she

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.346
says, you're home early.

00:14:23.346 --> 00:14:25.172
Did you forget something?

00:14:25.172 --> 00:14:29.570
I'm like, yeah, forgot
my life.

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:31.604
What do you mean by that?

00:14:31.604 --> 00:14:36.670
Well, are you in a good mood,
because I just quit my job.

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:37.920
She goes, really?

00:14:41.370 --> 00:14:44.460
So what are you going
to do now?

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:49.480
Well, thought I'd work on my
photography for a while.

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:53.390
Now, I knew I'd married the
right woman long ago.

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:56.520
But this just nailed
it for me.

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:59.230
And she can pretty much do
anything she wants--

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:00.630
I hope she doesn't see
this, because then

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:03.080
she'll know she can--

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:05.620
and I'll still stick with her.

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:08.740
Because she walks up, and
she gives me a big hug.

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:10.460
And remember how we talked
about being interactive.

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:12.380
You're going to have to
say aw in a moment.

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:15.920
She gives me a big hug, and she
whispers in my ear, it's

00:15:15.920 --> 00:15:17.170
about time.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:20.450
AUDIENCE: Aw.

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:29.310
RODNEY LOUGH JR: It took us a
whopping week to pack the

00:15:29.310 --> 00:15:33.620
house and get out
of New Jersey.

00:15:33.620 --> 00:15:34.870
And we moved to Colorado.

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:43.670
Now within the first five
minutes of this talk, you've

00:15:43.670 --> 00:15:47.500
probably decided whether
you love me or hate me.

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:52.350
And I've got to be honest,
either way, I don't care.

00:15:52.350 --> 00:15:54.570
Because I like me.

00:15:54.570 --> 00:15:55.730
I like me.

00:15:55.730 --> 00:15:58.160
I like the fact that I left
the corporate world.

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:00.970
I like the fact that I'm doing
what I love to do.

00:16:00.970 --> 00:16:02.720
I even like the fact
I keep winning all

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:04.230
these ridiculous awards.

00:16:04.230 --> 00:16:07.900
I've got so many awards
it's sick.

00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:09.910
You've heard of sick
money, right?

00:16:09.910 --> 00:16:11.870
People who have sick money.

00:16:11.870 --> 00:16:13.120
I have sick awards.

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:20.370
People shooting photography,
more questions.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:24.060
Anyone shooting medium-format
camera?

00:16:24.060 --> 00:16:26.280
How about large format?

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:29.640
One dude.

00:16:29.640 --> 00:16:33.340
You guys don't even know what
I'm talking about, do you?

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:36.740
You saw that picture of me
with the camera, right?

00:16:36.740 --> 00:16:42.640
Imagine a camera so large that
the film is that big.

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.370
That's how big my film is.

00:16:45.370 --> 00:16:47.780
Have you ever seen the old
camera with the bellows on

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:52.260
them, and you've got to put
your head under the hood?

00:16:52.260 --> 00:16:54.120
Everything on the back
i a ground glass.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:55.490
It's upside down
and backwards.

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:58.280
Have you guys seen this
kind of camera before?

00:16:58.280 --> 00:16:59.880
That's what I'm using.

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:03.180
They still make them, but
they've stopped making my

00:17:03.180 --> 00:17:05.490
film, which is kind
of unfortunate,

00:17:05.490 --> 00:17:08.040
but I have a stash.

00:17:08.040 --> 00:17:11.950
Because I'm on the Fuji film
talent team, I saw it coming.

00:17:11.950 --> 00:17:15.920
I have hundreds of sheets of
film sitting in the freezer to

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:18.310
use down the road.

00:17:18.310 --> 00:17:20.730
In order to be successful in the
business I do, you have to

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:21.510
have passion.

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:23.369
I think to be successful
in any business, you

00:17:23.369 --> 00:17:24.329
have to have passion.

00:17:24.329 --> 00:17:28.069
So my passion, what drives
me is I'm a soloist.

00:17:28.069 --> 00:17:28.510
Right?

00:17:28.510 --> 00:17:33.810
I love being out in the middle
of nowhere by myself.

00:17:33.810 --> 00:17:34.220
Why?

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:34.950
Well, let me ask.

00:17:34.950 --> 00:17:36.270
Anyone ever do that?

00:17:36.270 --> 00:17:37.730
Show of hands.

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:39.710
Out in the middle of nowhere,
by yourself.

00:17:39.710 --> 00:17:41.530
Nothing else like
it, is there?

00:17:41.530 --> 00:17:42.460
Pure silence.

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:46.010
So quiet you can hear the
ringing in your ears, which is

00:17:46.010 --> 00:17:52.180
the onset of tinnitus, which
comes with age unfortunately.

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:54.900
Most the time I'm about
11 miles or so back.

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:57.060
Oh my gosh, I'm only
halfway through.

00:17:57.060 --> 00:17:57.630
This is crazy.

00:17:57.630 --> 00:17:58.970
How am I going to
pull this off?

00:18:05.650 --> 00:18:08.690
Does Google have a mission
statement?

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:10.910
Anyone know it?

00:18:10.910 --> 00:18:14.540
Show of hands, who knows
it by heart?

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:16.940
Managers, you're going to want
to take note of the people who

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:18.190
didn't raise their hands.

00:18:21.430 --> 00:18:23.540
My mission statement--

00:18:23.540 --> 00:18:27.400
now realize, if I had wanted
to make money, becoming an

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:31.730
artist was probably not
the smartest move, OK?

00:18:31.730 --> 00:18:36.420
My mission statement is to
enrich people's lives by

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:40.520
bringing Rodney's nature-based
art into every home and office

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:41.770
in the world.

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:45.330
It's one sentence.

00:18:45.330 --> 00:18:47.000
It's a long sentence
and probably not

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.280
grammatically correct.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:52.950
I'm a math guy, not
an English guy.

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:55.850
But if you get rid of the
rhetoric, Rodney, Rodney,

00:18:55.850 --> 00:19:03.260
Rodney, and you boil it down to
its simplest form, enrich

00:19:03.260 --> 00:19:10.510
people's lives through nature,
that's what I'm seeking to do.

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:14.280
I've been fortunate enough that
it seems to be working.

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:18.390
But it only works because
I have the passion.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:26.390
I think I have time to
tell you this story.

00:19:26.390 --> 00:19:27.750
No I don't.

00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:29.080
I'm sorry, I don't.

00:19:29.080 --> 00:19:30.150
I don't.

00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:33.080
Normally I give convention
talks at Las Vegas or

00:19:33.080 --> 00:19:36.240
something, and they're two
hours, three hours.

00:19:36.240 --> 00:19:41.390
So to try and smush into
an hour is hard.

00:19:41.390 --> 00:19:42.540
My son--

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:46.070
I'm Rodney Lough Jr. That means
there was a senior.

00:19:46.070 --> 00:19:50.380
And that means, unfortunately,
there's a "the third."

00:19:50.380 --> 00:19:52.160
So uno, dos, tres.

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:53.790
We called him Trey.

00:19:53.790 --> 00:19:57.270
He doesn't even know how to
spell Rodney, because we've

00:19:57.270 --> 00:20:00.510
called him Trey his
whole life.

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:01.770
Trey's 19.

00:20:01.770 --> 00:20:04.710
He's got a fourth-degree black
belt in taekwondo.

00:20:04.710 --> 00:20:07.690
He's the youngest master to ever
receive that honor in the

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:09.800
United States.

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:12.310
Even I don't mess with
him, and I'm a lot

00:20:12.310 --> 00:20:14.330
bigger than he is.

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:17.150
But that's probably because
I love him, right?

00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:20.220
It's a father thing, I guess.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:23.100
Trey comes to me the other day,
and he says, dad, you're

00:20:23.100 --> 00:20:26.540
considered the best in the
world at what you do.

00:20:26.540 --> 00:20:28.620
Why?

00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:30.490
How is that?

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:31.030
No one had--

00:20:31.030 --> 00:20:31.720
I'd been asked--

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:33.740
I've been interviewed gobs.

00:20:33.740 --> 00:20:35.330
No one's ever asked
me that question.

00:20:35.330 --> 00:20:37.230
I thought, that was
a great question.

00:20:37.230 --> 00:20:38.310
Why?

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:41.770
I thought about for a little
bit, and I thought, hm,

00:20:41.770 --> 00:20:44.240
because I don't think I am.

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:45.450
Now that sounds crazy, right?

00:20:45.450 --> 00:20:50.330
A piece in the Smithsonian, an
award from the United Nations.

00:20:50.330 --> 00:20:57.180
I got something from the
US Senate, sick awards.

00:20:57.180 --> 00:20:58.870
But why?

00:20:58.870 --> 00:21:00.710
Why am I the best in the
world at what I do?

00:21:00.710 --> 00:21:02.435
Because I don't think I am.

00:21:02.435 --> 00:21:06.330
It constantly means that I'm
improving and looking at not

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:10.000
what's right but looking
at what's wrong.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.010
It's easy to stand in front of
a large mountain at sunrise,

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:15.430
with the thing just going off
and the stream in the

00:21:15.430 --> 00:21:18.710
foreground and everything's
perfect.

00:21:18.710 --> 00:21:21.150
And it's yelling at you,
photograph me.

00:21:21.150 --> 00:21:23.080
Please photograph me.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:26.240
Look how magnificent I am.

00:21:26.240 --> 00:21:28.020
Those are easy.

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:31.350
The in-between stuff, kind of
not the big mountains, just

00:21:31.350 --> 00:21:33.670
sort of uh, a little
more difficult.

00:21:33.670 --> 00:21:36.690
The intimate stuff,
really hard.

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:39.850
But in every one of those cases
I don't look at what's

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:41.040
right with it.

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:44.900
I'm constantly examining
what's wrong.

00:21:44.900 --> 00:21:49.720
I don't know if that makes
me weird, but it's got

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:50.970
me where I'm at.

00:21:53.170 --> 00:21:54.610
Oh my gosh.

00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:56.090
OK, my studio--

00:21:56.090 --> 00:22:00.380
I have an 18,000 square
foot studio.

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:04.280
It's just a teeny little
photography place.

00:22:04.280 --> 00:22:07.380
I've got a tango drum scanner,
where I convert my film from

00:22:07.380 --> 00:22:11.950
analog to digital, because you
can't even get print film for

00:22:11.950 --> 00:22:13.110
enlargers these day.

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:16.960
Everything has to be switched
over and converted to digital.

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:20.370
I have two backup scanners.

00:22:20.370 --> 00:22:24.460
I've got a 52-inch Colex
type C processor.

00:22:24.460 --> 00:22:26.110
Is this going over
everyone's head?

00:22:26.110 --> 00:22:27.970
Anyone know what I'm
talking about?

00:22:27.970 --> 00:22:29.280
I got some over my heads.

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:32.760
And I got a couple people
saying, I don't understand.

00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:33.870
But that's OK.

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:39.070
It basically allows me to go
like this, [WHISTLE], huh,

00:22:39.070 --> 00:22:44.704
that's magnificent, get out my
camera, come back, [WHISTLE]

00:22:44.704 --> 00:22:46.180
too-doo-loo.

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:50.070
Put it on the wall and
we all go, ahh.

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:52.100
Because that's it, right?

00:22:52.100 --> 00:22:53.190
Hah.

00:22:53.190 --> 00:22:54.440
Hah.

00:22:56.620 --> 00:22:59.700
That's what I do, try
and enrich people's

00:22:59.700 --> 00:23:00.930
lives through nature.

00:23:00.930 --> 00:23:03.640
The only way I can do that is
when I have that sensation,

00:23:03.640 --> 00:23:05.020
try and get it on the
wall so you guys

00:23:05.020 --> 00:23:06.270
can have that sensation.

00:23:09.240 --> 00:23:11.070
Long story short, I got
a remarkable studio.

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:12.570
You guys are welcome to
come up and visit.

00:23:12.570 --> 00:23:16.890
Like I said, just call ahead
so we can vacuum.

00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:20.090
I do have time for one story.

00:23:20.090 --> 00:23:22.860
When I do these photography
workshops every year--

00:23:22.860 --> 00:23:24.810
people come on these photography
workshops.

00:23:24.810 --> 00:23:27.300
They pay me, I think, outrageous
sums of money to

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:28.540
come and hike along.

00:23:28.540 --> 00:23:31.466
People say, what do I get
for my 2 and 1/2 days?

00:23:31.466 --> 00:23:33.950
Get to hang out with me.

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:36.190
That's what you get for
2 and 1/2 days.

00:23:36.190 --> 00:23:38.480
Now I will tell you,
I wear you out.

00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:40.740
Every night you're like
oh, I'm exhausted.

00:23:40.740 --> 00:23:42.800
But it's so much fun.

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:44.860
Well, in order to do these
workshops up in Glacier

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:47.750
National Park in Montana, you
have to have taken this bear

00:23:47.750 --> 00:23:49.030
encounter course.

00:23:49.030 --> 00:23:51.900
And they teach you how to deal
with bears, when you come up

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:53.740
on them in the wilderness.

00:23:53.740 --> 00:23:56.280
You take a submissive posture.

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:57.100
You're not loud.

00:23:57.100 --> 00:23:58.470
You kind of talk
to them softly.

00:23:58.470 --> 00:24:01.100
When they're not watching you,
you back away slowly.

00:24:01.100 --> 00:24:03.085
The moment they take
interest, you stop.

00:24:03.085 --> 00:24:06.280
They give you all
these scenarios.

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:10.050
I was up in British Columbia,
by myself, on this teeny

00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:12.580
little island called
[? Mala Illa Coola. ?]

00:24:12.580 --> 00:24:15.070
And I'm pretty sure I
just butchered it.

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:18.300
And I've moored my boat
on the beach.

00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:20.540
I'm hiking down this one little
trail that's got about

00:24:20.540 --> 00:24:24.650
this wide, blackberry bushes
going off on either side.

00:24:24.650 --> 00:24:28.995
And every, I don't know, eight
feet is a pile of bear scat.

00:24:28.995 --> 00:24:30.760
And I'm a guide in Glacier.

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:32.800
I know how to handle bears.

00:24:32.800 --> 00:24:37.470
Never had to really, but
I've been trained.

00:24:37.470 --> 00:24:38.980
Come around this little-- and
I'm doing all this stuff.

00:24:38.980 --> 00:24:39.910
I'm clapping my hands.

00:24:39.910 --> 00:24:42.350
Hey bear, here I come.

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:47.310
Come around this little corner
and right there is the butt

00:24:47.310 --> 00:24:50.380
end of a little black bear.

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:53.530
And I'm thinking to myself,
this is not something that

00:24:53.530 --> 00:24:57.220
they teach you in the bear
encounter course.

00:24:57.220 --> 00:24:59.460
What happens when you come up on
the butt end of the little

00:24:59.460 --> 00:25:00.480
black bear?

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:03.350
Because if you turn and go the
other way, and it hears you,

00:25:03.350 --> 00:25:05.320
the whole fight/flight
thing kicks in.

00:25:05.320 --> 00:25:06.060
The bear attacks you.

00:25:06.060 --> 00:25:08.190
It kills you, rips
your jugular out.

00:25:08.190 --> 00:25:11.440
I might be exaggerating a
little bit for effect.

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:14.320
But it's probably not good.

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:19.220
So I'm thinking to myself,
what can I do?

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:21.390
I know--

00:25:21.390 --> 00:25:22.280
true story--

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:25.980
as loud as I could, I
yelled, hey bear.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:28.190
And at the same time I slapped
it in the butt.

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:34.440
The bear went, oh,
his eyes huge.

00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:36.730
