00:37:51.320 --> 00:37:54.490
Cottonwood trees, looking at all
the other cars, and you're

00:37:54.490 --> 00:38:01.310
like, what's so great about
this Zion National Park?

00:38:01.310 --> 00:38:03.750
They go into the visitor's
center, where they got the

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:04.980
bookstores.

00:38:04.980 --> 00:38:07.470
And you look through the
postcards and the note cards

00:38:07.470 --> 00:38:10.760
and the posters and the picture
books and maybe even

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:13.020
spend a few bucks and
get some of them.

00:38:13.020 --> 00:38:15.010
And then you walk over
to the ranger.

00:38:15.010 --> 00:38:19.110
And you lay them on the table,
and you go, where are these?

00:38:19.110 --> 00:38:23.260
You guys know what the
ranger's job is?

00:38:23.260 --> 00:38:23.930
No one.

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:26.030
All right, let me tell you.

00:38:26.030 --> 00:38:31.180
The ranger's task is to
protect the resource.

00:38:31.180 --> 00:38:33.620
That's what their mandate
is, right?

00:38:33.620 --> 00:38:35.100
They want to protect it.

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:36.000
Why?

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:37.270
So it can be there for our

00:38:37.270 --> 00:38:40.350
childrens' childrens' children.

00:38:40.350 --> 00:38:42.340
I think it's a great mission.

00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:46.570
So he's going to say to
you, I don't know.

00:38:46.570 --> 00:38:47.060
I'm sorry.

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:48.310
I don't know.

00:38:50.330 --> 00:38:58.290
I'm not going to say he's lying,
but he's lying because

00:38:58.290 --> 00:38:59.420
of his mandate.

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:01.110
And I don't blame him really.

00:39:01.110 --> 00:39:03.060
Not too much.

00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:04.260
But he's going to
give you a map.

00:39:04.260 --> 00:39:07.820
And on that map is going
to be like 80 spots.

00:39:07.820 --> 00:39:08.830
Oh, this one's great.

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:09.430
And that one's great.

00:39:09.430 --> 00:39:10.260
You've got to go here.

00:39:10.260 --> 00:39:11.650
Check this one out.

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:13.980
I'm here to tell you that out
of those 80 places, there's

00:39:13.980 --> 00:39:17.550
like four of them that
are truly special.

00:39:17.550 --> 00:39:20.360
And there's another five
or six that aren't

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:22.350
even on that map.

00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:25.940
And I know it from spending
my entire life hiking and

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:28.100
exploring and whatnot.

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:31.850
On one of these chat rooms, a
friend of mine sent me a link

00:39:31.850 --> 00:39:34.940
to it, and it said,
Rodney Lough is--

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:38.255
he wastes all of his time
hiking around in

00:39:38.255 --> 00:39:39.530
the middle of nowhere.

00:39:39.530 --> 00:39:40.950
And maybe he finds something.

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:41.880
And maybe he doesn't.

00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:45.150
That's incredibly inefficient.

00:39:45.150 --> 00:39:47.040
I thought to myself, that's
kind of a ridiculous

00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:48.330
statement, isn't it?

00:39:48.330 --> 00:39:51.290
I mean, how do these
people think that

00:39:51.290 --> 00:39:53.180
these places get found?

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:56.290
Google Maps?

00:39:56.290 --> 00:40:00.010
Maybe, but how did
that get found?

00:40:00.010 --> 00:40:02.810
Oh, right, your feet.

00:40:02.810 --> 00:40:04.890
That's how they got found.

00:40:04.890 --> 00:40:12.070
All right, Stand Here is
a social media website.

00:40:12.070 --> 00:40:14.610
It's a mobile app.

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:20.250
It's a monthly syndicated
column.

00:40:20.250 --> 00:40:23.490
And with our fingers crossed
and our toes crossed, it's

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:25.620
also going to be a TV show.

00:40:25.620 --> 00:40:28.010
That's what we're working
on right now.

00:40:28.010 --> 00:40:31.710
Because our mission is
to enrich people's

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:33.560
lives through nature.

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:37.860
If I can tell people where
these places are--

00:40:37.860 --> 00:40:42.680
I believe that this concept of
keeping them secret and keeps

00:40:42.680 --> 00:40:44.770
them safe is a false.

00:40:44.770 --> 00:40:45.680
It's false.

00:40:45.680 --> 00:40:47.860
I've watched it destroy
places.

00:40:47.860 --> 00:40:50.970
I think the only way to protect
them is to create a

00:40:50.970 --> 00:40:54.750
community of people who
understand how beautiful they

00:40:54.750 --> 00:40:59.730
are and work and seek to protect
these few places that

00:40:59.730 --> 00:41:03.070
are really out there in the
gigantic national park.

00:41:03.070 --> 00:41:04.660
I'm not saying that the whole
park isn't pretty.

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:07.630
It is, but there are
special places.

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:10.810
Those are the ones we
need to protect.

00:41:10.810 --> 00:41:13.170
So that's what Stand
Here is all about.

00:41:13.170 --> 00:41:17.500
So if you guys have the ability
to help create Stand

00:41:17.500 --> 00:41:20.940
Here, in the public awareness,
so we can protect the

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:24.400
beautiful places in our national
parks, by all means,

00:41:24.400 --> 00:41:26.240
please help us do so.

00:41:26.240 --> 00:41:29.870
Because we're taking all
of our funds and--

00:41:29.870 --> 00:41:30.550
well, not all of them.

00:41:30.550 --> 00:41:31.860
We have bills to pay, right?

00:41:31.860 --> 00:41:35.050
But we're going to take money
and donate back to each one of

00:41:35.050 --> 00:41:37.120
these places to protect them.

00:41:37.120 --> 00:41:39.200
Did you know that when you
donate money to a national

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:41.980
park, you can tell them exactly
how you want them to

00:41:41.980 --> 00:41:43.570
spend the money?

00:41:43.570 --> 00:41:45.080
You can.

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:47.890
On this trail I want you to take
this segment right here

00:41:47.890 --> 00:41:49.890
and I want you to improve
the trail.

00:41:49.890 --> 00:41:51.440
Here I want you to make sure
that duh, duh, duh.

00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:54.040
You can tell them exactly
what to do.

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:55.510
And that's what we're
going to do.

00:41:55.510 --> 00:41:59.950
We're going to create a
community of people who care.

00:41:59.950 --> 00:42:02.780
Being highly-educated,
intelligent people that you

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:05.600
are at Google, you must
certainly understand the

00:42:05.600 --> 00:42:08.530
importance of what I'm
talking about.

00:42:08.530 --> 00:42:11.540
Because guys like me are
going to die someday.

00:42:11.540 --> 00:42:15.570
And the knowledge will die too,
unless it gets passed on,

00:42:15.570 --> 00:42:19.220
and it's carried on from
generation to generation.

00:42:19.220 --> 00:42:22.670
I know, it's something we've
heard before, but it's true.

00:42:22.670 --> 00:42:26.260
You get to a point in your
life and you go, oh, if I

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:28.950
don't share this, it
could be lost.

00:42:28.950 --> 00:42:32.170
I don't want to see
that happen.

00:42:32.170 --> 00:42:33.730
Thank you, guys,
for having me.

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:34.980
Appreciate it.

00:42:39.100 --> 00:42:41.210
I did it.

00:42:41.210 --> 00:42:44.080
Any questions?

00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:44.480
Yes, sir.

00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:46.671
AUDIENCE: Have you been film all
your life, or do you also

00:42:46.671 --> 00:42:48.820
mix in with digital techniques,
like capture

00:42:48.820 --> 00:42:50.700
techniques?

00:42:50.700 --> 00:42:52.820
RODNEY LOUGH JR: I've been
shooting digital--

00:42:52.820 --> 00:42:56.650
or, I'm sorry, film since I
was 12, all the way up to

00:42:56.650 --> 00:42:58.500
about three years ago.

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:03.280
A company had asked me to take
out a 65 megapixel digital

00:43:03.280 --> 00:43:05.280
back and play with it.

00:43:05.280 --> 00:43:07.010
I think what they wanted was--

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:08.720
they wanted me to say
it's as good as the

00:43:08.720 --> 00:43:11.120
8x10, click for click.

00:43:11.120 --> 00:43:12.720
And it wasn't, so I
couldn't do it.

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:14.370
And I gave it back to them.

00:43:14.370 --> 00:43:17.940
And then about a year and a half
ago, they came out with

00:43:17.940 --> 00:43:19.590
an 80 megapixel digital back.

00:43:19.590 --> 00:43:22.540
And they asked me to go out
and do the same thing.

00:43:22.540 --> 00:43:26.780
And it does not match, click
for click, with the 8x10.

00:43:26.780 --> 00:43:29.050
But because of all the
techniques that are available

00:43:29.050 --> 00:43:31.350
now, where you can take multiple
pieces and put them

00:43:31.350 --> 00:43:34.070
together, I can actually
get something that is

00:43:34.070 --> 00:43:36.490
very close to 8x10.

00:43:36.490 --> 00:43:38.060
We're not quite there yet.

00:43:38.060 --> 00:43:41.720
The moment they can give me
something that captures a gig

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:44.630
in a single shot, and it's
like the size of a credit

00:43:44.630 --> 00:43:48.470
card, I'm all over it.

00:43:48.470 --> 00:43:50.920
So I have started to switch,
because they

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:52.030
stopped making my film.

00:43:52.030 --> 00:43:54.750
I've got no choice, sadly.

00:43:54.750 --> 00:43:57.670
So I've got about 400
sheets of 8x10

00:43:57.670 --> 00:43:59.570
film left in the freezer.

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:02.690
And then I've got this 80
megapixel digital back that I

00:44:02.690 --> 00:44:07.980
put on a 4x5 pancake technical
field camera, because the

00:44:07.980 --> 00:44:10.990
lenses have what's called
an image circle.

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:12.820
Basically what it can see.

00:44:12.820 --> 00:44:16.050
And I can move that back within
that image circle, even

00:44:16.050 --> 00:44:20.660
though I've applied a tilt or a
swing or a shift, which, for

00:44:20.660 --> 00:44:22.600
most of you, doesn't
mean anything.

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:23.300
Anything else?

00:44:23.300 --> 00:44:23.540
Yeah.

00:44:23.540 --> 00:44:26.510
AUDIENCE: You've got-- how many
sheets of film do you

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:28.420
shoot on a typical
hike for a day?

00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:29.671
AUDIENCE: Can you repeat
the question?

00:44:29.671 --> 00:44:31.760
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Yeah, the
question was, when I go out on

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:34.910
a day hike, how many sheets of
film do I take with me, and

00:44:34.910 --> 00:44:36.200
how many shots do I take?

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:38.380
Did I get that right?

00:44:38.380 --> 00:44:39.360
It depends.

00:44:39.360 --> 00:44:42.140
I can go out for three weeks and
not take a single thing,

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:44.450
because I just don't
find anything.

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.840
Or I can go out, and
in one evening

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:47.930
it just goes ballistic.

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:50.090
And I'll go through everything
in my bag.

00:44:50.090 --> 00:44:54.120
But typically, if I'm a day
hike, I'll carry five film

00:44:54.120 --> 00:44:55.970
holders with me, which
carries 10 sheets.

00:44:55.970 --> 00:44:59.390
Because there's two sheets
per film holder.

00:44:59.390 --> 00:45:01.270
And I can blow through
that in a day.

00:45:01.270 --> 00:45:03.700
But it's $50 a click.

00:45:03.700 --> 00:45:07.026
So I'm Scottish, right?

00:45:07.026 --> 00:45:08.520
A pretty frugal guy.

00:45:08.520 --> 00:45:12.110
And I evaluate it pretty good
before I rip up $50.

00:45:12.110 --> 00:45:16.046
AUDIENCE: So do you usually
shoot just one

00:45:16.046 --> 00:45:18.014
frame of each scene?

00:45:18.014 --> 00:45:19.490
And then do you always
print them?

00:45:19.490 --> 00:45:22.950
RODNEY LOUGH JR: The question
was if I just shoot one frame

00:45:22.950 --> 00:45:26.690
or one sheet of film for
every composition?

00:45:26.690 --> 00:45:28.380
No, not necessarily.

00:45:28.380 --> 00:45:30.950
Rarely will I shoot
one piece of film.

00:45:30.950 --> 00:45:33.270
Usually it's always two.

00:45:33.270 --> 00:45:35.440
Because the first one--

00:45:35.440 --> 00:45:37.600
I shoot both sheets of film
exactly the same.

00:45:37.600 --> 00:45:39.010
And then I'll process one.

00:45:39.010 --> 00:45:40.790
And then I'll look at it and
make a determination.

00:45:40.790 --> 00:45:43.430
Do I need to push it or pull it
in processing, which means,

00:45:43.430 --> 00:45:45.770
do I need to make it lighter
or darker in processing,

00:45:45.770 --> 00:45:47.630
because I under-exposed
it or maybe I slightly

00:45:47.630 --> 00:45:48.950
over-exposed it.

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:50.460
And I'll do that post.

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:53.280
But I shoot everything exactly
the same in the field.

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:56.730
I don't use any color filters,
no polarizers.

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:59.730
I do have a graduated neutral
density filter, which allows

00:45:59.730 --> 00:46:01.680
me to hold back the
bright sky.

00:46:01.680 --> 00:46:04.430
But because it's a neutral
gray, it doesn't add or

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:06.760
subtract any color,
it just adds-- or

00:46:06.760 --> 00:46:08.600
actually subtracts density.

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:10.730
So it keeps the light
from coming through.

00:46:13.580 --> 00:46:14.580
And then do I actually
print them?

00:46:14.580 --> 00:46:15.750
Yeah, that was actually
in the section I

00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:17.790
skipped over on the studio.

00:46:17.790 --> 00:46:21.270
I've got my own LightJet
430 digital enlarger.

00:46:21.270 --> 00:46:28.910
I can do up to maximum one
image, 50 inches by 10 feet.

00:46:28.910 --> 00:46:31.367
And if I wanted to, I could take
that piece and stand it

00:46:31.367 --> 00:46:34.050
vertical and then put
pieces together to

00:46:34.050 --> 00:46:35.000
make it even larger.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.290
Yep.

00:46:37.290 --> 00:46:37.530
Yeah?

00:46:37.530 --> 00:46:39.036
AUDIENCE: How do you
decide where to go?

00:46:39.036 --> 00:46:42.210
RODNEY LOUGH JR: How do
I decide where to go?

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:44.930
When I first started, I did
these little outdoor art

00:46:44.930 --> 00:46:47.320
festivals all over
the country.

00:46:47.320 --> 00:46:49.710
And so I would end up usually
end up going, what's between

00:46:49.710 --> 00:46:50.920
this spot and the next spot?

00:46:50.920 --> 00:46:52.640
And that's kind of
where I went.

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:55.290
I haven't done those
in like 10 years.

00:46:55.290 --> 00:46:59.170
But now I pretty much get
to go wherever I want.

00:46:59.170 --> 00:47:04.690
Tomorrow morning I fly down to
Managua, in Nicaragua, because

00:47:04.690 --> 00:47:07.000
the president is getting
one of my pieces.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:08.720
And I'm there to
give it to him.

00:47:08.720 --> 00:47:12.720
Because I went there last year
and photographed Nicaragua and

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:14.065
actually had a blast.

00:47:14.065 --> 00:47:15.380
It was a lot of fun.

00:47:15.380 --> 00:47:16.630
So it just depends.

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:18.570
Sometimes I get lucky, and
someone says, hey, you want to

00:47:18.570 --> 00:47:19.005
go to Nicaragua?

00:47:19.005 --> 00:47:21.470
I'm like, Yeah, sure.

00:47:21.470 --> 00:47:22.990
Other times it's like, oh,
I've got to work in the

00:47:22.990 --> 00:47:25.020
studio, so I can't.

00:47:25.020 --> 00:47:27.380
But if it's going off some
place like tonight-- for

00:47:27.380 --> 00:47:30.060
example, if we were anywhere
to the north, there's an

00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:31.260
aurora alert.

00:47:31.260 --> 00:47:32.910
I don't know how many
of you know that.

00:47:32.910 --> 00:47:35.120
But if you were up in Anchorage,
you'd be watching

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.900
the Aurora Borealis tonight in
full swing, because it's at a

00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:41.317
level four, which is big.

00:47:41.317 --> 00:47:44.796
AUDIENCE: How many days a year
do you spend out in the field

00:47:44.796 --> 00:47:45.293
photographing?

00:47:45.293 --> 00:47:46.784
How many days in studio
developing?

00:47:46.784 --> 00:47:49.766
And how many days talking
through the business stuff,

00:47:49.766 --> 00:47:50.263
making sure [INAUDIBLE]?

00:47:50.263 --> 00:47:52.140
RODNEY LOUGH JR: You are so
a programmer, aren't you?

00:47:56.510 --> 00:47:58.440
Out in the field, not enough.

00:47:58.440 --> 00:48:00.200
In the studio, too much.

00:48:00.200 --> 00:48:01.210
What was the other one?

00:48:01.210 --> 00:48:02.440
AUDIENCE: Stuff like this.

00:48:02.440 --> 00:48:04.310
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Oh, doing
stuff like this.

00:48:04.310 --> 00:48:05.080
I give like--

00:48:05.080 --> 00:48:07.090
I don't know-- four or
five talks a year.

00:48:07.090 --> 00:48:09.910
So I think my next talk is--

00:48:09.910 --> 00:48:12.480
I think it's next
month in WPPI.

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:16.110
It's a big convention
in Las Vegas.

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:19.270
And then I've been asked to come
down to Disney and give a

00:48:19.270 --> 00:48:21.620
talk to the imagineers.

00:48:21.620 --> 00:48:27.750
It'll probably be a group just
like yourselves, all PhDs with

00:48:27.750 --> 00:48:29.000
a sense of humor.

00:48:31.100 --> 00:48:32.460
At least I saw some smiles.

00:48:32.460 --> 00:48:33.400
That's good.

00:48:33.400 --> 00:48:34.100
Any other questions?

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:34.350
Yeah.

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:36.420
AUDIENCE: So I'm a little
disappointed.

00:48:36.420 --> 00:48:37.320
I don't see your rig.

00:48:37.320 --> 00:48:38.955
I was kind of hoping you would
show us how heavy it was.

00:48:38.955 --> 00:48:41.650
RODNEY LOUGH JR: If I wasn't
going to Nicaragua, I actually

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:42.300
would have brought it.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:42.800
Yeah.

00:48:42.800 --> 00:48:44.010
I had planned on bringing it.

00:48:44.010 --> 00:48:44.930
AUDIENCE: How heavy is it?

00:48:44.930 --> 00:48:48.300
And do you feel like you've got
some special muscles for

00:48:48.300 --> 00:48:50.240
carrying it that most
people don't?

00:48:50.240 --> 00:48:51.760
It's kind of funny, in this
world, where everyone carries

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:52.086
their iPhones.

00:48:52.086 --> 00:48:53.062
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Do me a favor.

00:48:53.062 --> 00:48:54.530
Stand up.

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:58.150
OK, so that's you,
and this is me.

00:48:58.150 --> 00:49:01.890
I'm huge, right?

00:49:01.890 --> 00:49:04.600
So if I put--

00:49:04.600 --> 00:49:07.100
the backpack, without any
camping gear in it, is

00:49:07.100 --> 00:49:10.490
probably pushing
55, 60 pounds.

00:49:10.490 --> 00:49:13.440
If I'm going out for a
week or more, it'll

00:49:13.440 --> 00:49:16.650
pop up to 110, 120.

00:49:16.650 --> 00:49:19.490
Right now I'm carrying what
I call my survival layer.

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:21.850
And so if I--

00:49:21.850 --> 00:49:23.100
get it, right?

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:26.410
So if I carry that camera out in
the woods for a few weeks,

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:28.405
the survival layer goes
away really fast.

00:49:28.405 --> 00:49:30.990
AUDIENCE: And how do you
fly with the camera?

00:49:30.990 --> 00:49:34.050
RODNEY LOUGH JR: I put it in
one of those foamy deals.

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:35.960
I take the whole thing
apart, lenses.

00:49:35.960 --> 00:49:39.260
I lock it up and throw it
on there and pick it up.

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:41.840
And then I leave that usually
at the airport, because you

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:44.270
can do that, and put
everything in my

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:47.550
backpack and then go.

00:49:47.550 --> 00:49:50.932
Yeah, pretty slick some of the
stuff you can do these days.

00:49:50.932 --> 00:49:51.384
Yeah.

00:49:51.384 --> 00:49:55.110
AUDIENCE: How many miles
do you hike a day?

00:49:55.110 --> 00:49:56.890
RODNEY LOUGH JR: When
I'm in the field?

00:49:56.890 --> 00:49:59.000
Not when I'm sitting at
my desk in my office?

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.730
OK.

00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:04.490
Well, on average, I'm
probably back about

00:50:04.490 --> 00:50:07.350
11 miles, on average.

00:50:07.350 --> 00:50:09.840
There's a lot of stuff that's
easy to get to.

00:50:09.840 --> 00:50:14.670
There's some stuff that's not
too hard to get to, a day or

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:16.030
two to get into.

00:50:16.030 --> 00:50:17.900
And then there's some stuff
that's two, three

00:50:17.900 --> 00:50:20.290
weeks to get into.

00:50:20.290 --> 00:50:24.800
So on average, I guess
I'm probably--

00:50:24.800 --> 00:50:27.040
well, on Sunday I had a
friend from Moscow.

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:28.310
He came to visit.

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:29.940
And he's like, I want
to go shoot.

00:50:29.940 --> 00:50:33.950
And I'm like, it's fricking
24 degrees outside.

00:50:33.950 --> 00:50:34.860
What?

00:50:34.860 --> 00:50:36.910
Yeah, let's go up
in the gorge.

00:50:36.910 --> 00:50:38.050
So I thought, fine.

00:50:38.050 --> 00:50:39.260
I'll take him on this
little hike.

00:50:39.260 --> 00:50:41.910
It's two miles in,
two miles out.

00:50:41.910 --> 00:50:44.520
I have what I call the
two mile rule.

00:50:44.520 --> 00:50:48.830
At two miles all
the jerks stop.

00:50:48.830 --> 00:50:49.510
They do.

00:50:49.510 --> 00:50:51.580
Because they're like,
do, do, do--

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:52.280
two miles.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:54.350
Oh my gosh, that's four miles.

00:50:54.350 --> 00:50:56.950
I don't want to-- four miles.

00:50:56.950 --> 00:50:59.240
This tail we went on was
just covered with ice.

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:00.340
There's a part where you've
got to hold the

00:51:00.340 --> 00:51:01.340
cable to get by.

00:51:01.340 --> 00:51:02.340
And it's like this wide.

00:51:02.340 --> 00:51:04.090
And it was just a
sheet of ice.

00:51:04.090 --> 00:51:05.780
And as we're going through--
his name is Dimitri.

00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:07.780
He's from Russia, so he's
probably used to some ice.

00:51:07.780 --> 00:51:10.510
I'm like, are you having fun?

00:51:10.510 --> 00:51:11.710
Because it was dangerous.

00:51:11.710 --> 00:51:12.570
It was really dangerous.

00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:15.500
But on Sunday I did a
four miler, just a

00:51:15.500 --> 00:51:18.110
nice little day hike.

00:51:18.110 --> 00:51:20.730
Yeah, in the back.

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:21.485
Oh, hold on.

00:51:21.485 --> 00:51:22.670
I'm getting two people.

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:24.874
We'll start here, and then
we'll come to you.

00:51:24.874 --> 00:51:28.248
AUDIENCE: Do you have any
dangerous situations?

00:51:28.248 --> 00:51:30.616
RODNEY LOUGH JR:
Do I have any--

00:51:30.616 --> 00:51:32.350
AUDIENCE: Dangerous
situations.

00:51:32.350 --> 00:51:34.990
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Have I had
any dangerous situations?

00:51:34.990 --> 00:51:39.520
I kind of think the black bear
was pretty dangerous.

00:51:39.520 --> 00:51:42.440
One of my favorite sayings is,
when I'm doing workshops--

00:51:42.440 --> 00:51:44.850
because some of places we go to,
there's no fence, and I'm

00:51:44.850 --> 00:51:47.500
like, this is life.

00:51:47.500 --> 00:51:49.180
That is death.

00:51:49.180 --> 00:51:49.800
Right?

00:51:49.800 --> 00:51:53.080
There are absolutely
situations.

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:55.240
I don't have it to show you, but
there's this photograph I

00:51:55.240 --> 00:51:57.790
have of me standing on this
precipice, where the rock

00:51:57.790 --> 00:51:58.820
comes back underneath.

00:51:58.820 --> 00:52:01.500
And it's easily like
a 1,200 foot drop.

00:52:01.500 --> 00:52:03.930
But that was the only place I
could get the angle I wanted.

00:52:03.930 --> 00:52:05.820
so I went out there.

00:52:05.820 --> 00:52:08.210
I think you have to have a
couple missing screws to do

00:52:08.210 --> 00:52:09.780
some of the stuff I do.

00:52:09.780 --> 00:52:10.846
Yeah.

00:52:10.846 --> 00:52:13.552
AUDIENCE: How do you sell
your photographs?

00:52:13.552 --> 00:52:14.911
What is your business model?

00:52:14.911 --> 00:52:17.560
On your website, I couldn't
see that you had these

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:20.868
"dropped in a basket" tactics.

00:52:20.868 --> 00:52:23.358
How do you sell these
photographs?

00:52:23.358 --> 00:52:26.720
RODNEY LOUGH JR: I currently
have four galleries.

00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:28.730
I have one up in Happy Valley.

00:52:28.730 --> 00:52:30.280
I have one in Sausalito.

00:52:30.280 --> 00:52:32.080
I have one in Las Vegas.

00:52:32.080 --> 00:52:33.980
And then I have one
at Fisherman's

00:52:33.980 --> 00:52:36.460
Wharf in San Francisco.

00:52:36.460 --> 00:52:38.360
So my own galleries primarily.

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:39.020
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:52:39.020 --> 00:52:40.830
So you don't sell online?

00:52:40.830 --> 00:52:42.020
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Not right now.

00:52:42.020 --> 00:52:42.400
No.

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:45.550
Our website used to
do online stuff.

00:52:45.550 --> 00:52:48.010
But what we discovered, from
our collector base, is they

00:52:48.010 --> 00:52:51.090
really just wanted to look at
the images and then call one

00:52:51.090 --> 00:52:54.620
of the people at the gallery
and make their final

00:52:54.620 --> 00:52:55.820
decisions that way.

00:52:55.820 --> 00:52:58.110
So we tried to make our new
website, which is up and

00:52:58.110 --> 00:53:03.220
running right now, to be more
artsy, I guess, and less

00:53:03.220 --> 00:53:04.278
commercial.

00:53:04.278 --> 00:53:06.966
Yep.

00:53:06.966 --> 00:53:09.885
AUDIENCE: You mentioned taking
people out on workshops,

00:53:09.885 --> 00:53:10.940
photography clients--

00:53:10.940 --> 00:53:12.230
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Not
British people.

00:53:15.390 --> 00:53:16.160
I'm joking.

00:53:16.160 --> 00:53:16.920
I'm joking.

00:53:16.920 --> 00:53:20.696
AUDIENCE: Can the Americans
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:53:20.696 --> 00:53:22.584
So everyone's been to
the same place.

00:53:22.584 --> 00:53:24.010
They've all been exposed
to the same landscape.

00:53:24.010 --> 00:53:26.585
I'm curious as to how their
different shots compare.

00:53:26.585 --> 00:53:28.680
In other words, how much of it
is being there, and how much

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:30.080
is having the right eye?

00:53:30.080 --> 00:53:30.990
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Remember,
we were talking

00:53:30.990 --> 00:53:32.640
earlier about talent.

00:53:32.640 --> 00:53:35.260
I've actually looked through a
lot of other people's cameras

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:36.190
over the years.

00:53:36.190 --> 00:53:38.065
And some people absolutely
have it,

00:53:38.065 --> 00:53:39.500
and some people don't.

00:53:39.500 --> 00:53:39.790
All right?

00:53:39.790 --> 00:53:43.010
And I can't explain why that is,
other than this concept of

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:45.820
we all have different
talents, right?

00:53:45.820 --> 00:53:50.180
But I've had five, six people on
this side of me, five, six

00:53:50.180 --> 00:53:51.090
people on the side of me.

00:53:51.090 --> 00:53:52.630
We're all looking at
the same thing.

00:53:52.630 --> 00:53:55.290
And I go look at their cameras,
and every single one

00:53:55.290 --> 00:53:58.640
of them is different.

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:00.490
It's really unique, actually.

00:54:00.490 --> 00:54:03.170
It's kind of fun.

00:54:03.170 --> 00:54:04.706
Anything else?

00:54:04.706 --> 00:54:05.542
Yep.

00:54:05.542 --> 00:54:08.110
AUDIENCE: When and why do
you choose nature to

00:54:08.110 --> 00:54:09.030
be your main subject?

00:54:09.030 --> 00:54:11.680
RODNEY LOUGH JR: When and why
do I choose nature to be my

00:54:11.680 --> 00:54:13.890
main subject?

00:54:13.890 --> 00:54:16.320
Have you spent much
time out there?

00:54:16.320 --> 00:54:17.070
Yeah?

00:54:17.070 --> 00:54:18.010
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:18.010 --> 00:54:19.330
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Yes, OK.

00:54:19.330 --> 00:54:22.690
Well that would be the short
answer, wouldn't it?

00:54:22.690 --> 00:54:28.410
I think that there is a
peacefulness and a calming,

00:54:28.410 --> 00:54:32.320
serene feeling that
can only come from

00:54:32.320 --> 00:54:35.480
being in these places.

00:54:35.480 --> 00:54:39.520
I don't know what a typical
workspace here at Google looks

00:54:39.520 --> 00:54:42.153
like, but I'm assuming
you have a cube.

00:54:42.153 --> 00:54:44.910
You have a cube, or is it
just-- yeah, cubes.

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:47.610
Everyone's got cubes.

00:54:47.610 --> 00:54:49.050
Let me tell you something.

00:54:49.050 --> 00:54:54.230
We weren't designed to work
and live in cubes.

00:54:54.230 --> 00:54:57.060
We weren't designed to
walk on concrete.

00:54:57.060 --> 00:54:58.520
We were given grass.

00:54:58.520 --> 00:55:02.640
That's what we're supposed
to be walking on.

00:55:02.640 --> 00:55:06.260
It's OK that not everyone gets
to do what I do, because that

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:10.340
means I don't run into as many
people when I'm out there.

00:55:10.340 --> 00:55:12.410
And I'm grateful to you guys.

00:55:12.410 --> 00:55:13.520
I seriously am.

00:55:13.520 --> 00:55:16.670
My guys at the studio were
working on Stand Here.

00:55:16.670 --> 00:55:21.750
And your Google Maps
API, they love it.

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:23.800
If they could give you
guys a medal--

00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:24.880
Any Google Map guys in here?

00:55:24.880 --> 00:55:26.680
There was one, wasn't there?

00:55:26.680 --> 00:55:28.870
Yeah, they'd give you a map--

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:29.760
or a medal.

00:55:29.760 --> 00:55:31.000
They totally would.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.890
They love you guys.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:35.830
But no, I do it because I
love being out there.

00:55:35.830 --> 00:55:37.150
Absolutely.

00:55:37.150 --> 00:55:40.160
I just grew up with
it, I guess.

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:40.670
Yep.

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:42.500
AUDIENCE: How many people
in your crew?

00:55:42.500 --> 00:55:47.480
RODNEY LOUGH JR: I have, right
now, pushing 50 people that

00:55:47.480 --> 00:55:48.690
work with me.

00:55:48.690 --> 00:55:52.130
And I say with me as opposed
to for me, because often

00:55:52.130 --> 00:55:55.040
they're doing a lot of
things for me that I

00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:56.580
don't even know about.

00:55:56.580 --> 00:56:00.010
And they can only do that
when they work with you.

00:56:00.010 --> 00:56:01.640
Do you understand the-- do you
guys understand what I'm

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:03.680
saying, the difference of
working for somebody and

00:56:03.680 --> 00:56:05.260
working with somebody?

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:07.270
My people are working with me.

00:56:07.270 --> 00:56:09.010
And I love it.

00:56:09.010 --> 00:56:12.970
We've tried to create an
environment of people--

00:56:12.970 --> 00:56:14.940
remember, I talked about
the two-mile rule?

00:56:14.940 --> 00:56:17.660
Well, the people that you meet
beyond the two miles are what

00:56:17.660 --> 00:56:20.930
I call earth muffins.

00:56:20.930 --> 00:56:24.110
Come on, they've got
the dreadlocks.

00:56:24.110 --> 00:56:26.600
The women don't shave
their armpits.

00:56:26.600 --> 00:56:27.450
You know what I'm
talking about?

00:56:27.450 --> 00:56:29.350
These are earth muffins.

00:56:29.350 --> 00:56:30.360
I work--

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:32.410
even though they don't have
dreadlocks, and they do shave

00:56:32.410 --> 00:56:36.240
their pits, I work with a
bunch of earth muffins.

00:56:36.240 --> 00:56:40.020
They're like the sweetest,
nicest people on the planet.

00:56:40.020 --> 00:56:41.330
I have a great life.

00:56:41.330 --> 00:56:43.720
I really do.

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:46.366
One more question, then
I think we're done.

00:56:46.366 --> 00:56:49.190
AUDIENCE: So how has
this sort of--

00:56:49.190 --> 00:56:51.070
I feel like in the last decade
or so, there's kind of an

00:56:51.070 --> 00:56:53.560
increase in democratization
of photography.

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:57.070
I feel like more people have
pro-level photography gear in

00:56:57.070 --> 00:56:57.640
their hands.

00:56:57.640 --> 00:56:59.730
More people are taking pictures
with lesser cameras,

00:56:59.730 --> 00:57:01.520
all the way down to
iPhones and stuff.

00:57:01.520 --> 00:57:03.950
How is that affecting the demand
for your products in

00:57:03.950 --> 00:57:04.650
your business?

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:07.050
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Actually,
it's improved it.

00:57:07.050 --> 00:57:08.250
The question was--

00:57:08.250 --> 00:57:09.550
I don't know if you guys
heard it or not.

00:57:09.550 --> 00:57:11.400
There's a lot of people out
there with cameras.

00:57:11.400 --> 00:57:13.530
There's a lot of people who
fancy themselves as

00:57:13.530 --> 00:57:15.590
photographers.

00:57:15.590 --> 00:57:18.370
How has that affected
my business?

00:57:18.370 --> 00:57:19.930
Actually, it's helped it.

00:57:19.930 --> 00:57:24.200
Because when you look at what
other people have for the

00:57:24.200 --> 00:57:26.700
price points that they charge,
and then you come look at

00:57:26.700 --> 00:57:29.700
mine, it's like a no-brainer.

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:33.190
If you've never been to my
gallery in San Francisco, it's

00:57:33.190 --> 00:57:34.220
not that far away.

00:57:34.220 --> 00:57:36.250
Has anyone been there?

00:57:36.250 --> 00:57:39.340
OK, so you even know what I'm
talking about, don't you?

00:57:39.340 --> 00:57:41.470
AUDIENCE: I think it's worth
pointing out though to people,

00:57:41.470 --> 00:57:43.845
it's different to look at the
pictures in the gallery than

00:57:43.845 --> 00:57:44.540
it is online.

00:57:44.540 --> 00:57:47.260
He has lighting in the gallery
that makes a big difference.

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:48.510
And the size of the prints
make a big difference.

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:50.270
RODNEY LOUGH JR: Let's be
clear about one thing.

00:57:50.270 --> 00:57:52.060
I take photos.

00:57:52.060 --> 00:57:54.470
You take pictures.

00:57:54.470 --> 00:57:56.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:56.970 --> 00:57:59.200
RODNEY LOUGH JR: I'm just
messing with you, man.

00:57:59.200 --> 00:57:59.710
I don't--

00:57:59.710 --> 00:58:02.260
he's probably like the senior
VP of all of Google or

00:58:02.260 --> 00:58:03.940
something, isn't he?

00:58:03.940 --> 00:58:04.760
Screwed that.

00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:06.550
AUDIENCE: Does a different
fraction--

00:58:06.550 --> 00:58:09.620
is the fraction of money that
you get coming more from the

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:12.000
workshops and less from the
photos or anything like that?

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:12.590
RODNEY LOUGH JR: No.

00:58:12.590 --> 00:58:16.516
The fine art photography is
where I make my money.

00:58:16.516 --> 00:58:17.210
Yep.

00:58:17.210 --> 00:58:19.280
That's where we feed the
kids and pay the

00:58:19.280 --> 00:58:20.440
orthodontist bills.

00:58:20.440 --> 00:58:25.080
And that's where it's at.

00:58:25.080 --> 00:58:28.520
What we're doing with Stand
Here, we actually don't know

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:30.000
that we're going to
make any money.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:32.200
We don't want to
lose any money.

00:58:32.200 --> 00:58:33.860
But by the same token,
we think it's a

00:58:33.860 --> 00:58:35.400
greater mission, right?

00:58:35.400 --> 00:58:38.430
It's not about making
gobs of money.

00:58:38.430 --> 00:58:41.610
It's about making people's
lives better.

00:58:41.610 --> 00:58:44.280
In the end, that's ultimately
what I want to be remembered

00:58:44.280 --> 00:58:49.430
by, protecting truly beautiful
places and making people's

00:58:49.430 --> 00:58:50.880
lives better.

00:58:50.880 --> 00:58:53.613
Is that such a horrible thing
to have on your tombstone?

00:58:53.613 --> 00:58:56.510
I don't think so.

00:58:56.510 --> 00:58:58.040
All right, I think we're done.

00:58:58.040 --> 00:58:59.590
I want to thank you guys
for having me out.

00:58:59.590 --> 00:59:00.840
Really appreciate it.

